I’ve spent a lot of time over the last few weeks in Mexico reflecting. One morning during my meditation I realized something that I want to share in case any of you feel the same.

I spent a lot of years in my 20’s trying to be sunshine in human form. I wanted to be the person that made other people’s lives brighter and more fun. I wanted to bring energy and joy to people’s days, and of course to my own. I wanted to spread as much light as I could at all times.

The more time I spent meditating on this I realized, maybe I want to be moonlight in human form. The moon is energizing, and calming but also more cyclical. The sun is nonstop and never burns out. But as we know, humans can’t burn forever before we burn out.

The moon comes and goes, takes its time waxing and waning. Shining light and filling us with energy, then taking a step back and letting us energize ourselves. 

I’ve always felt more connected to the moon. The feminine to the sun’s masculine. The quiet, consistent force that makes waves across the planet. 

So that’s my vision for 2023. Be moonlight in human form. 🌙 
.
.
And here’s a collection of images from my camera roll that feel like moonlight to me 🫶🏼

Some days are easier to find gratitude than others, but over the years I’ve found a few ways to increase gratitude in my life. And the great part about a gratitude practice is that each time you do it, it gets easier to find things to be grateful for!

1. Spend time being actively present. Use all of your senses to be aware of your surroundings, fully seeing, hearing, feeling etc makes it easier to recognize the gifts around us. Maybe it’s a scented candle or a fuzzy blanket or birds chirping, but there is always something that can bring us joy if we’re paying attention.
2. Write in a gratitude journal. I use the 5 Minute Journal by @intelligentchange but a regular notebook works too. Write down what you’re grateful for at the beginning and end of each day. It can be small or big. If you’re struggling to get started, pick a theme. Family, home, travel… something that comes to mind easily, and go from there.
3. Get outside, spend time in nature. Whether it’s a snowy walk or sitting on a beach.. time outside is so grounding and such a great reminder of how great life is outside of the confines of our sometimes busy homes.

#travel #travelinspo #playadelcarmen #photographerlife #gratitude #gratitudepractice #gratitudejournal

New Years Resolutions got you down? Listen, you could hop on a flight and GTFO of here OR you can take my advice:

1. Habit formation takes time. Get a habit tracker, write down each time you accomplish your task. Trying to get better at creating content on IG? Make a realistic goal and track it. Want to drink more water? Give yourself a ✔️ every day you hit your goal. 

2. Don’t bite off more than you can chew. Master a few habits, once they become part of who you are then start a new one. If you still need your habit tracker to remember, it’s not part of you yet. 

3. Remember there’s such a thing as self-improvement burnout. If you want to take a day off, take a day off. Don’t go so hard that you quit entirely.  If the first month of the year didn’t go to plan, that’s what the other 11 are for.

Small habits when done daily will change your life.

YOMO am I right? Who needs a wedding budget? Well, unfortunately.. most of us. So how do you make sure you get your dream wedding without sacrificing on what’s most important to you??

1. Write out your priorities. What is an absolute non-negotiable for you when you picture your dream wedding? Stunning florals? Amazing food? Beautiful photography & videography? Being clear with yourself and your partner about your priorities will help you decide where to allocate $$

2. Don’t pull numbers out of nowhere. Do some research on what your priorities might cost - if something is high on your list, this isn’t an area to skimp on. Find vendors at low, medium, and higher pricing and pay attention to how they differ. Trust us when we say, there is a very big difference between options and the pricing and experience will reflect that!

3. Practically, there are ways to make your dream wedding happen even if you’re working with a lower budget. Have a longer engagement, a smaller guest list, a less traditional wedding date (hello Thursdays!)… keep in mind that peak dates, locations, and large guests lists will all = higher costs. 

In the end, be honest with yourself and your vendors about your priorities and your budget. We want you to have the perfect day and not have to take out a second mortgage on your house to do it.

Wedding ✨details✨ Let's discuss. ⁠
⁠
A wedding's aesthetic and overall vibe is brought together by little (and sometimes big) details. That's why it's so important to make sure you have intentionally planned time in to your schedule to photograph these on your wedding day! Here are a few tips to make sure your details are all perfectly captured on your wedding day:⁠
⁠
1. Have your jewellery, invitation suite, shoes, veil, etc. all set aside for your photographer's arrival. I like to start by styling a flatlay of your pieces, and the easiest way to do this is if you've collected all of your items in one spot before we arrive! 🌸 bonus points if you have asked your florist for some loose blooms that we can pop into your flatlay to incorporate your floral design without having to put your entire bouquet into the image 🌸⁠
⁠
2. Plan to get ready in a beautiful, well-lit space. If you've always loved bridal portraits with a certain aesthetic, make sure the location you choose suits your vibe! Airbnb's, photography studios, even unused rooms at your venue can make for beautiful getting-ready photos. Hotel rooms are often darker, and can get filled with bridesmaids/groomsmen's *stuff* really quickly. If you opt for a hotel room, try to keep it clutter-free and ask for one with the most space and light.⁠
⁠
3. Make sure there is time set aside for us to photograph your ceremony and reception rooms without guests! Typically we can pop into the ceremony space before the doors are open for guests, but if you've planned a gorgeous design for your reception space, make sure we've set aside time in the schedule for us to photograph the entire room, head table, and table settings prior to guests sitting down and putting bags and jackets at their seats! ⁠
⁠
👇🏻 Questions about details?? Leave them below!! 👇🏻⁠
Natalie + Conor’s wedding morning moments ✨🥂

Are you having trouble figuring out what flatlay styling elements to use for your wedding photos? Want to make sure all of your details are displayed in a way that represents your overall wedding aesthetic? ⁠
⁠
I *love* putting together flatlays for my clients, styling your details is one of my favourite ways to start the day. In order to create your flatlays, there are a few things that you can set aside to make sure I have enough elements to work with.. here are a few suggestions!⁠
⁠
✨ invitation suite & stamps (even better if you have custom stamps made from your engagement photos like natalie & conor's!)⁠
✨ shoes⁠
✨ perfume⁠
✨ loose blooms & greenery - ask your florist to deliver some along with your bouquets⁠
✨ a ring box or jewellery tray that matches your wedding colours⁠
✨ jewellery & accessories (don't forget watch, cufflinks, and tie for the groom!)⁠
✨ vow books⁠
✨ sunglasses⁠
✨ any other unique details that make your wedding yours!⁠
⁠
What elements are you planning to include in our flatlay? Let me know in the comments!! ⁠And don’t forget to save this post for your big day 💍

I had lunch with a friend yesterday. His name is Robert, he's 77 years old and he's been a professional musician his entire life. Weirdly enough, we have a lot in common. Just like me, he loves to tell a story.

Yesterday he was telling me about a time he was playing a show with a pretty well known band. He's one of the best guitar players I've ever heard. There's something about listening to him play that makes you stop and pay attention. At the end of the show, a guy came up to him and said "I want to be just like you. 
How do I do it? I want to play guitar like you, travel, and get paid as a musician".

Robert's response was "what are you willing to give up?". He said the guy was stunned. He didn't understand. Robert said, "To get to this level, you have to be willing to give something up."

For Robert, he had to give up the dream of a steady relationship, a big house with kids playing in the yard, free time, a consistent income.

Of course, for him what he got was *worth* those sacrifices. I know that, because there is no way he would still be a working musician at 77 unless it WAS worth it. He gave up so much, but in return he got to be the best of the best. He has a career he loves. He gets to be creative, work with other passionate and talented musicians. He gets to listen to and make music all day long. And that was worth it for him.

At the end of the story I realized, again, how much we have in common. In one of the very first mindset modules in Better Than Booked, I ask everyone to think about what they value.

Knowing what you value is SO critical in life and business because it is the guiding light that helps with every decision we make. In my life I value freedom: time, money, decisions.. I like being the one in the driver's seat of my life.
But just like Robert, I have had to give up a lot as well. Weekends with my family & friends, "normal" hours, fitting in in a society that really wants women to settle down and have kids by 30, the financial stability (or at least promise of it) that comes with a 9-5.

(Cont. in comments)

I won’t lie, I got a little teary-eyed during this session. Seeing clients through seasons of life is seriously magical, and watching Paulina & Dan go from engaged, to married, to expecting their first babe and now as parents was pure joy.

But what got me tearing up was seeing Dan become a Dad, and watching him as he admired his baby boy. Seriously, my heart burst open. It was like you could see the awe in his eyes as he held Benjamin and it was just such a pure Dad moment. 

So Happy Father’s Day to all the amazing Dads out there, and a special happy first Father’s Day to all the new Dads :) Enjoy every minute.

January 1st hits and I immediately start thinking about what’s next. Usually that comes with criticism of what I wish I had done more of, less of, done differently etc in the previous year. That’s why I love doing this. Taking a look back at where the year started, where we’ve been, what we’ve accomplished (both tangibly and not) isn’t just nice to do.. it’s self care for perfectionists 🥹

Shooting SO many beautiful and *intentional* weddings has been a highlight. From Cabo to Big Sur to our home town. Thank you to everyone who has asked me to document your day.. 10 years in, I feel more blessed each year I get to do this.

Working with family and branding clients that become friends. Documenting life’s big moments: celebrating the wins and also being a safe place to land during some of my clients hardest moments.. I feel honoured every time I get to play a role in your lives. 

This year also took me to Hawaii to co-host @bookfocal Not-A-Conference, Arizona to share my love of @imagen.ai, Vegas for @wppievents to help grow @bookfocal, and right here to Waterloo to host and speak at @canadaphotosummit. 

I launched my first comprehensive course for photographers #BetterThanBooked, and mentored dozens of photographers one-on-one to help them grow their own businesses that they love. Stepping more into the role of photography + business educator has been SO rewarding and I’m excited to do more of that this year. 

In between all that I managed to take time for myself, my family and friends. Vacations with my girlfriends, countless adventures with @taylorjackson, cottage weekends with my family, and of course nursing my giant meatball back to health after knee surgery. 

It’s been a heck of a year and somehow it still feels like I’m just getting started.

This year I’m looking forward to a bit of levity. Taking life a little less seriously, and getting a bit more weird with each passing year….

So… let’s go 🪩🤝🤠
